    <section id="most-of-what-america-calls-recycling-is-a-performance-but-not-all-of-it" class="reveal">
  <h2>Most of what America calls "recycling" is a performance. But not all of it.</h2>
  <p>Five percent. That's the share of U.S. plastic waste that actually gets recycled. Not 20%. Not the cheery 30-something percent that the chasing-arrows symbol on your yogurt cup implies. Five.</p>
  <p>Meanwhile, 60–64% of American paper finds a second life. Aluminum cans get melted down and returned to store shelves in under 60 days. Three-quarters of all the aluminum humanity has ever smelted is still in productive use right now, cycling through the economy like currency.</p>
  <p>The popular framing that recycling is a scam is half right, which makes it fully wrong.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-plastic-con" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Plastic Con</h2>
  <p>The petrochemical industry knew by 1969 that post-consumer plastic recycling was, in the words of its own American Chemical Society document, unlikely to work "on a broad basis." Internal conference notes from that era describe the economics as "virtually hopeless." The founding director of the Vinyl Institute told attendees in 1989 that recycling "cannot go on indefinitely, and does not solve the problem."</p>
  <p>They spent the next three decades telling the public the opposite.</p>
  <p>By the late 1980s, polls showed Americans souring on plastic. Bans loomed. So the industry bankrolled recycling infrastructure, lobbied for the resin identification code system (those numbered triangles that look exactly like recycling symbols because they were designed to), and ran feel-good advertising at scale. The goal was never to recycle plastic. The goal was to make plastic <em>feel</em> recyclable long enough to kill the legislative momentum for bans and production limits.</p>
  <p>It worked. A 2024 Center for Climate Integrity report, drawing on newly disclosed industry documents, lays out the playbook with prosecutorial clarity. One American Plastics Council official's meeting notes warned that virgin material would "kick the s–t out of" recycled plastic on price. They were right. It still does. And that single economic fact is why plastic recycling rates have barely moved in 30 years.</p>
  <p>The physics are just as hostile. Plastic is a polymer, built from long molecular chains that degrade every time they're mechanically reprocessed. Unlike metals, which are elemental and reform without structural loss, plastic <em>downcycles</em>. Your recycled water bottle doesn't become another water bottle. It becomes carpet fiber, or a park bench, or landfill liner, none of which will be recycled again. The loop doesn't loop.</p>
  <p>Chemical recycling, the industry's latest pitch, promises to break plastic down to its molecular constituents and rebuild it. The concept has existed for decades. The results haven't followed. Most operational facilities convert plastic into fuel to be burned, not back into plastic. One industry consultant summarized the state of play in 2024: "We've had a few successes and a ton of failures... things look grim."</p>
  <p>Global plastic production hit 400 million metric tons in 2022. The recycling rate held at 9%. In the U.S., it was 5%. The gap between those numbers and the public's perception of them is not an accident. It was purchased.</p>
</section>

<section id="why-aluminum-works" class="reveal">
  <h2>Why Aluminum Works</h2>
  <p>Aluminum recycling works because the economics demand it.</p>
  <p>Producing primary aluminum from bauxite ore requires electrolysis, one of the most energy-intensive industrial processes on earth: 186 gigajoules per ton. Recycling aluminum requires 8.3 gigajoules. A 95% energy savings. No marketing campaign is needed to make recyclers interested in a 95% discount on their largest input cost.</p>
  <p>That's the difference between a recycling system propped up by subsidies, mandates, and public guilt and one that generates profit on its own terms. A ton of recycled aluminum cans is worth $1,338. A ton of recycled PET plastic is worth $215. A ton of recycled glass carries a <em>negative</em> value of $23.</p>
  <p>The material science cooperates too. Aluminum is elemental. Melt it, reform it, and its crystalline structure is unchanged. There is no downcycling. A can becomes a can becomes a can, indefinitely, with roughly 1% melt loss per cycle. The closed-loop circularity rate for aluminum beverage cans in the U.S. hit 96.7% in 2023, meaning almost all recycled aluminum goes right back into the same product. PET bottles manage 34%. Glass lands between 30% and 60%.</p>
  <p>The average American aluminum can already contains 71% recycled content. More than 80% of U.S. aluminum production comes from recycled sources. And 75% of all aluminum ever produced in human history remains in active use.</p>
  <p>Yet the U.S. can recycling rate has actually <em>fallen</em>, from a historical average of 52% to just 43% in 2023, the lowest point in decades. Americans threw away roughly $1.2 billion worth of aluminum that year. The material works. The collection infrastructure doesn't. It's aging, single-stream recycling contaminates aluminum with other materials, and 9% of the U.S. population still lacks access to a program that accepts cans. States with bottle deposit laws recycle at roughly double the rate of those without.</p>
  <p>Japan recycles over 90% of its aluminum cans. Brazil hits 98%. The American number reflects policy failure, not material limitation.</p>
</section>

<section id="paper-boring-functional-real" class="reveal">
  <h2>Paper: Boring, Functional, Real</h2>
  <p>Paper recycling in America processes 125,000 tons per day. In 2024, the national rate was 60–64%, with cardboard at 69–74%. Eighty percent of U.S. paper mills now use recycled fiber, and the recycled share of all fiber consumed at domestic mills has climbed from 36.6% in 2005 to 44.4% in 2024.</p>
  <p>The economics are less dramatic than aluminum but still solid. Recycling paper saves about 60% of the energy required to produce it from virgin wood pulp. One recycled ton spares the equivalent of 17 trees and 7,000 gallons of water.</p>
  <p>Paper does degrade with each cycle. Fibers shorten and weaken through reprocessing. But the degradation is manageable: paper can typically be recycled five to seven times, and spent fibers still find use in egg cartons or insulation. The system runs at genuine scale, and the industry has invested billions since 2019 in mill capacity designed primarily for recovered material.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-uncomfortable-sorting" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Uncomfortable Sorting</h2>
  <p>Three materials share a bin. They have almost nothing else in common.</p>
  <p>Aluminum recycling is an economic no-brainer hamstrung by lazy infrastructure policy. Paper recycling is a functioning system that could be better. Plastic recycling, at least the consumer curbside variety, is for the vast majority of resins not recycling in any meaningful sense. It is an elaborate, industry-funded misdirection that has successfully delayed production limits for half a century.</p>
  <p>The honest response is to stop pretending these are the same activity. Treating "recycling" as a single category, whether to praise or condemn, obscures the actual policy question, which is material-specific.</p>
  <p>For aluminum: expand bottle deposit programs, fund collection infrastructure, and stop losing a billion dollars a year to landfills out of sheer inattention.</p>
  <p>For paper: maintain and invest in the existing system, which is working.</p>
  <p>For plastic: stop asking consumers to sort their way out of a production problem. The chasing arrows on a polystyrene clamshell are not a recycling instruction. They are, by the industry's own internal admission, a public relations strategy. The appropriate response to a material that cannot be economically or physically recycled at scale is not better bins. It is less material.</p>
  <p>The recycling bin is not one conversation. It is three, sharing a container.</p>
</section>
